[3]
Date: 7 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Singapore - Ministry of Health 7 Apr 2003 [edited]
<http://app.moh.gov.sg/new/new02.asp?id=1&mid=5961>

SARS Update - 7 Apr 2003
As of 7 Apr 2003, 73 SARS patients have been discharged. 31 SARS patients
remain hospitalised.
There were 7 additional SARS cases reported today. All are nurses; 1 from
TTSH, 2 from SGH, 2 from CGH, 1 from a private nursing home and 1
radiographer from SGH.
Nurse from TTSH
A nurse from TTSH who had come into contact with a SARS patient before the
patient was diagnosed with SARS was admitted on 28 Mar 2003 as a suspected
SARS patient. She has since been upgraded to a probable SARS.
Nurses from CGH
2 nurses from CGH have been admitted to TTSH on 5 and 6 Apr 2003 as
probable SARS cases. One had close contact with a patient before she was
diagnosed with SARS and transferred to TTSH 21 Mar 2003. This SARS patient
was infected when she visited her sister in TTSH. At that time, a SARS
patient who had yet been diagnosed was in warded next to her sister at
TTSH. CGH had put the whole ward staff on voluntary quarantine and were
followed up closely. On 2 Apr [2003], the nurse who had attended to the
SARS patient was admitted to a single room at CGH as the clinical picture
then was suggestive of dengue fever. She was later diagnosed as a probable
SARS when her third chest x-ray showed changes. Her colleague who attended
to her when she admitted has now been diagnosed with SARS.
Private nursing home
A nurse from a private nursing home was admitted to CGH on 4 Apr 2003 for
pneumonia and transferred to TTSH on 6 Apr 2003 for probable SARS. He is
now in serious condition in intensive care.
His girlfriend, who is also a nurse at the same nursing home, was admitted
to TTSH on 7 Apr 2003 as a suspected SARS. Her condition is stable.
Investigations have revealed that a resident of the nursing home was
admitted to CGH on 25 Mar 2003 and died of pneumonia on 30 Mar 2003. This
nursing home resident had been earlier discharged from TTSH on 23 Mar 2003
for non-SARS related condition. When the patient was in TTSH she was warded
next to a patient who was later diagnosed as a SARS case. The male nurse
from the nursing home had been attending to this resident.
Update on cluster of SGH staff
Arising from the transfer of staff and patients of SGH Wards 57 and 58, a
total of 29 have been admitted to the SARS wards. Of these, there are 4
probable SARS cases (a doctor and 2 nurses), 18 suspected SARS cases and 7
admitted for observation. They are all stable.
There were a total of 346 patients who were discharged from Wards 57 & 58
during the period 20 Mar 2003 - 5 Apr 2003. So far, 284 have been contacted
about their well being. All of them including their immediate family
members and friends who visited them when they were in SGH are well.
As an assurance, visitors who went to Wards 57 and 58 at SGH from 20 Mar
2003 to 5 Apr 2003 may call SGH hotline at 6321-3591 between 8.00 AM and
10.00 PM for free health checks to ensure their well-being. Investigations
are on-going to determine the source of infection for these hospital staff.
2 SARS patients in intensive care passed away today. One is the mother of
the first index case and the other a TTSH doctor who had attended to a SARS
patient before she had been diagnosed with SARS. This patient has since
passed away on 29 Mar 2003.
Today, 7 passengers from affected areas required further screening by the
nurses at the airport. None were referred to TTSH for further assessment.
No passenger vessels that had a travel history to SARS affected areas in
the last 10 days arrived today.
The Ministry would like to reiterate that we have taken steps to safeguard
our public transport system. There is thus no need for commuters to avoid
taxis, buses or the MRT in fear of contracting SARS.
Special arrangements have been made for 4 categories of persons with a
higher likelihood of getting SARS:
(a) Persons with Home Quarantine Order who would have come into direct
contact with a SARS patient
(b) Cases identified by General Practitioners and private dentists
(c) Incoming passengers from affected countries who received a Health Alert
Notice; and
(d) Cases identified during medical screening at Changi Airport and
Singapore Cruise Centre
People belonging to any of the above categories who develop SARS symptoms
should call the hotline number that they have been given. Upon receiving
such calls, MOH will arrange for a private ambulance to pick them up and
send them to TTSH directly for medical assessment. These people should not
take public transport or call relatives for transport arrangements.
Summary: to date, the total number of people diagnosed with SARS is 113.
Among these are 3 children below 18 years of age. Out of the 31 patients
still hospitalised, 12 are in intensive care. Since yesterday, there were 2
deaths and 1 new admission to intensive care who is the nurse from the
private nursing home.
Apart from the first imported case, the 6 other imported cases have not
given rise to any SARS cases.
The number of suspect cases admitted is 73, including 3 children (below 18
years old). The number of people under Home Quarantine Orders is 133.
--
