Source: Taiwan - Department of Health [accessed 7 Apr 2003 10:30 AM EST;
edited]
<http://203.65.72.83/En/dpc/ShowPublication.ASP?RecNo=844>

The majority SARS are imported, no community spread
As of 6 Apr 2003, with 3 new imported cases and one new probable case
infected by close contact with a Hong Kong case, a cumulative total of 19
probable cases have been identified in Taiwan. 5 of them have been
discharged, and the other 14 are still hospitalized.
The SARS outbreak in Taiwan is mainly sporadic and imported, with only 4
cases resulting from close contact (limited to primary transmission.) When
looking into the case data, 3 close contact with probable cases raised from
the 1st case; the 4th close contact case could have been avoided had his
brother not traveled while ill.
3 of the 4 newly identified probable cases are imported from various parts
of China. The flights taken were CX402 on 30 Mar 2003 and BR818 on 23 Mar
2003. One of the residents of Amoy Gardens, Hong Kong, flew to Taiwan to
visit his brother on 26 Mar 2003 (CX460, seat 35G). He stayed for 3 days
and returned to Hong Kong on 28 Mar 2003 (CX511, seat 42H). He was reported
to be symptomatic before 26 Mar 2003 and was hospitalized after returning
to Hong Kong, and his Taiwanese brother was also hospitalized on 3 Apr 2003
because of fever and pneumonia. The Center for Disease Control had the list
of all passengers sitting in the same seat row and within 3 rows in front
of or behind on the same flights (n=51). We have initiated follow-up for
the 25 Taiwanese passengers [in this possibly exposed group].
--
