[7]
Date: 7 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Newswire briefs [edited]

[A] China - from ABC news 7 Apr 2003
<http://abcnews.go.com/wire/Living/ap20030407_733.html>
Chinese officials had reported 43 SARS deaths in the southern province of
Guangdong, where experts suspect the illness originated, with fatalities
also coming in Beijing and the Guangxi region. On Monday, Chinese state
television reported that there were also one SARS death each in the
provinces of Shanxi in the north, Sichuan in the west, and Hunan in central
China, the first fatalities in those areas, and an indication the disease
was more widespread geographically than previously acknowledged.
[B] Vietnam - from an AFP newswire report
The 5 new cases, confirmed at Hanoi's Bach Mai hospital over the weekend
include a doctor who treated a 67-year-old man hospitalised last Wednesday
in serious condition and 4 members of his family. All the new patients come
from Ninh Binh province, 100 kilometers (62 miles) south of Hanoi. The
67-year-old, whose son had undergone surgery in the SARS-hit French
hospital in Hanoi, apparently constitutes a new source of the
disease. Another man who came into close contact with him in Ninh Binh was
also hospitalized, on Thursday, bringing the province's suspected cases to
7. Local health workers in Ninh Binh province have quarantined about 50
people who had contact with the initial patient.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to the WHO statistics presented in [1][A], as of today, there is
a cumulative total of 2601 cases of SARS, with 98 deaths, reported from 17
countries. This represents an increase of 85 cases and 9 deaths compared
with the last WHO update of 5 Apr 2003. Hong Kong continues that have the
largest number of new cases on a daily basis with 41 cases reported in the
past 24 hours. The number of new cases associated with the Amoy Gardens
apartment block appears to be decreasing, but there continue to be other
new cases for which the transmission/contact level is not presented. We
await further information on the studies conducted on the apartment block
to shed light on possible route of transmission. While it had appeared that
transmission had been interrupted in Hanoi, Viet Nam, after 10 days with no
new cases reported (equal to approximately one incubation period) there now
seems to be a new generation of transmission, with a case occurring outside
of Hanoi, and several other cases in health care workers exposed to the
case. The newswire briefs mention the provinces involved with new reports
of cases in both China and Viet Nam. As mentioned in the newswire, in Viet
Nam, the new generation of cases is related to the original outbreak in Hanoi.
Further clarification of the numbers of secondary and more transmissions
that have occurred in the USA and Taiwan would be of interest. The reports
from both these regions suggest a few isolated incidences of secondary
transmission to close family contacts. We also await more technical
details on the etiology of this disease and the laboratory component of the
investigation. - Mod.MPP]
